# Nowhere discovery endpoint (baked default) -- example/template. Copy to /data/nowhere/discovery.conf
# (or bake at /system/etc/nowhere/discovery.conf) and fill in. LF line endings only (a CR breaks parsing).
#
# A fresh device with NO data store reads this to BOOTSTRAP its store config from name+passphrase: on a
# login the daemon GETs a sealed config object at an unguessable bootstrapRef(name,pass) here, unseals it,
# and configures itself -- so a profile re-materializes on any Nowhere device without re-entering store
# creds. The discovery endpoint only ever sees opaque refs -> ciphertext (zero-knowledge), like the data
# store. Enrollment (CREATE) + each login auto-PUBLISH the sealed config back here.
#
# KEYLESS LOOKUP (recommended, DIA-20260615-44): leave DISCO_ACCESS_KEY/SECRET BLANK and make the
# discovery bucket PUBLIC-READ. The daemon then bootstraps over an ANONYMOUS HTTP GET -> a fresh device
# needs NO baked creds at all (the leaked-image risk of an account-level key is gone from the bootstrap
# path). Safe because discovery only holds SEALED blobs at UNGUESSABLE refs (zero-knowledge): anyone can
# read the bucket, but a config only unseals with its name+passphrase. Endpoint + bucket are enough.
#   -> Filebase/S3: set the bucket (or the ref/ prefix) to public-read.
#
# WITH KEYS (legacy / also-publish): if you fill the keys, the daemon uses authenticated S3 (and can also
# PUBLISH on enrol/login). That bakes a long-lived key in the image -- only do this for a private bucket /
# dev. Publishing on a keyless device is skipped (it just looks up); scoped WRITE tokens are the Phase-2
# broker. For dev, discovery can even point at the same store as the data (bootstrapRef != profileRef).
DISCO_ENDPOINT=https://s3.example.com
DISCO_REGION=us-east-1
DISCO_BUCKET=nowhere-discovery
# Leave these BLANK for keyless anonymous lookup against a public-read bucket (the secure default):
DISCO_ACCESS_KEY=
DISCO_SECRET_KEY=
